          "content": "`format_alithya.py` generates a formatted Alithya-branded Word document from a Markdown file. Here's the flow:\n\n**1. Configuration**\n- Reads settings from `.env`: template file (`template_ref.docx`), output file (`generated.docx`), content file (`content.md`), list numbering ID, and line spacing.\n- Can also accept `content.md` and output filename as CLI arguments.\n\n**2. Parse Markdown → XML**\n- Reads `content.md` and parses it line by line.\n- Converts each Markdown element into raw Word XML (`<w:p>` paragraphs):\n  - `# / ## / ###` → `Heading1/2/3` styles (with auto-normalization — if only `###` is used, it maps to level 1)\n  - Numbered lists (`1. ...`) → `TexteAlithya` style with `<w:numPr>` numbering. If the item starts with `**bold text**`, it splits into a bold label + normal rest.\n  - Regular text → `TexteAlithya` style paragraphs\n  - `<aside>` blocks → treated as special text/table sections\n  - Empty lines → empty paragraphs\n- Strips Markdown formatting (bold `**`, italic `*`, backticks) and leading emojis/numbers from headings.\n\n**3. Inject into Template**\n- Opens `template_ref.docx` (which is a ZIP containing Word XML).\n- Reads `word/document.xml` and replaces the `<!-- CONTENT -->` placeholder with the generated XML paragraphs.\n- The template already has 4 sections: cover page, table of contents, content placeholder, and last page.\n\n**4. Write Output**\n- Copies every file from the template ZIP into a new `generated.docx`, swapping only `word/document.xml` with the modified version.\n- All styles (`Heading1`, `TexteAlithya`, `ListParagraph`) and numbering definitions come from the template — the script doesn't define any styling itself.\n\n**5. Manual Step**\n- After opening in Word, you need to press `Ctrl+A → F9` to refresh the table of contents since Word TOC fields can't auto-update programmatically.\n\nIn short: it's a Markdown-to-Word converter that injects content into a pre-styled Alithya template by manipulating the underlying XML directly."
        }
